questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - In both vertically and horizontally integrated firms&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Asymmetric information&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Asymmetric information arises when one party in a transaction or relationship has more or better information than the other.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This can lead to issues like moral hazard and adverse selection, where decisions or outcomes are skewed due to the imbalance of information.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In the context of firms, asymmetric information becomes significant when there is a lack of proper communication or transparency between different levels or divisions of an organization.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In vertically integrated firms&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Vertically integrated firms control multiple stages of production or distribution within the same supply chain (e.g., a company owning both manufacturing and retail operations).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Asymmetric information can arise here due to the complexity of managing operations across different stages, leading to inefficiencies and potential miscommunication between departments.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For example, the production division may not share accurate forecasts with the distribution division, leading to either overproduction or stock shortages.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In horizontally integrated firms&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Horizontally integrated firms operate at the same level of the supply chain but expand by acquiring or merging with competitors (e.g., two companies in the same industry combining resources).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Here, asymmetric information can result from differences in management styles, organizational culture, or operational priorities between the entities that merged or were acquired.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For instance, if one branch has more detailed market data than another, it may lead to uneven resource allocation or strategic inefficiencies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In both vertically and horizontally integrated firms&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Given the challenges discussed above, it is evident that asymmetric information can arise in both types of integrated firms.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In vertically integrated firms, the issue stems from managing multiple stages of production or distribution, while in horizontally integrated firms, it arises due to differences between merged entities.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Thus, the problem is not exclusive to one type of integration and can exist in both scenarios, making this the correct answer.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Horizontal Integration&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Horizontal integration refers to a business strategy where a company acquires or merges with other companies operating at the same level of the supply chain.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is often used to achieve economies of scale, reduce competition, and increase market share.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vertical Integration&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Vertical integration involves controlling multiple stages of the production or distribution process within the same company.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It can be divided into two types: forward integration (moving closer to the customer, e.g., owning retail outlets) and backward integration (securing supply chains, e.g., owning raw material sources).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Moral Hazard and Adverse Selection&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Moral hazard occurs when one party takes excessive risks because they do not bear the full consequences of their actions (e.g., employees misusing company resources due to lack of oversight).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Adverse selection refers to a situation where one party benefits from asymmetric information, leading to suboptimal outcomes (e.g., hiring an underqualified person due to lack of information about their skills).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;option 2.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Fiscal Deficit&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Fiscal Deficit refers to the &lt;strong&gt;financial situation wherein the government&amp;#39;s total budget exceeds the total receipts excluding borrowings made during the fiscal year.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, it can be expressed as&lt;strong&gt; Fiscal Deficit = Total Expenditure &amp;ndash; Total Receipts Excluding Borrowings.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;Government Security is a tradeable instrument issued by the Central Government or the State Government.&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It acknowledges the &lt;strong&gt;Government&amp;rsquo;s debt obligation.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;G-Secs carry practically no risk of default &lt;/strong&gt;and, hence, are called &lt;strong&gt;risk-free gilt-edged instruments. These form part of the fiscal deficit of the government. &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, option 2 is correct.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​Off-balance sheet is a mode of financial borrowing&lt;/strong&gt; where the Public Sector borrows money from the market under internal and extra-budgetary resources (IEBR) and funds government expenditure.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Once these companies raise the necessary amount, these get reflected as liabilities on their balance sheets and not on the central government&amp;rsquo;s budget documents.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In this case, &lt;strong&gt;off-sheet borrowings by the Food Corporation of India don&amp;#39;t impact the government&amp;#39;s fiscal deficit.&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, option 1&amp;nbsp;is not correct.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​A grant is not considered as part of the debt as it is not required to be paid back.&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Thus, there is &lt;strong&gt;no re-payment to be done for the World Bank grant received (by the government) in the previous financial years.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Consequently,&lt;strong&gt; it doesn&amp;#39;t part of the government&amp;#39;s fiscal deficit&lt;/strong&gt;. &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, option 3&amp;nbsp;is not correct.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Recapitalization bonds are dedicated bonds to be issued at the behest of the government for recapitalizing the troubled hit Public Sector Banks (PSBs).&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The government will issue&lt;strong&gt; bonds worth to PSBs&lt;/strong&gt; against equity shares.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This then becomes a cash-neutral transaction (instead of a direct cash infusion).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The&lt;strong&gt; funds mobilized from the sale of the bonds do not form a part of the fiscal deficit.&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, option 4&amp;nbsp;is not correct.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - quantity demanded varies directly with price.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Giffen&amp;#39;s Paradox&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Giffen&amp;#39;s Paradox refers to a situation where the quantity demanded of a good increases as its price increases, which is contrary to the law of demand.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This phenomenon typically occurs in the case of inferior goods that form a substantial part of a consumer&amp;#39;s budget.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;When the price of such goods rises, the real income of the consumer decreases. To compensate, the consumer may reduce consumption of superior goods and buy more of the inferior good, even at a higher price.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For example, if bread (a Giffen good) becomes more expensive, a low-income household might buy more bread because it cannot afford costlier alternatives like meat or vegetables.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Other Options&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Quantity demanded varies indirectly with price&lt;/strong&gt;

		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;This describes the typical relationship in the law of demand, where an increase in price leads to a decrease in quantity demanded. However, this is not applicable in the case of Giffen goods, which defy this norm.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Quantity demanded varies directly with income&lt;/strong&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;This relationship applies to normal goods, which see an increase in demand as consumer income rises. Giffen goods, being inferior goods, do not follow this pattern.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Quantity demanded varies indirectly with income&lt;/strong&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;This applies to inferior goods in general, where an increase in income reduces the demand for the good. However, Giffen goods are a specific subset of inferior goods with unique characteristics, making this broader definition insufficient.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following statements are correct&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;about the Public Distribution System (PDS)?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. It&amp;nbsp;is an Indian food Security System established under the Ministry of Consumer Affairs, Food, and Public Distribution.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;2. It is operated under the joint responsibility of the Central and the State Governments.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;3. It maintains the buffer stock of food grains in the warehouse.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Select the correct answer using the codes given below:&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1, 2 and 3.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It&amp;nbsp;is an &lt;strong&gt;Indian food Security System &lt;/strong&gt;established under the &lt;strong&gt;Ministry of Consumer Affairs, Food, and Public Distribution.&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Hence&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Statement 1&amp;nbsp;is correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Public Distribution System&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;strong&gt;PDS&lt;/strong&gt;) evolved as a&lt;strong&gt; system of management of scarcity&lt;/strong&gt; through the &lt;strong&gt;distribution of food grains at affordable prices.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It helps in &lt;strong&gt;ensuring the Food and Nutritional Security&lt;/strong&gt; of the &lt;strong&gt;nation&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;PDS &lt;/strong&gt;is &lt;strong&gt;supplemental in nature&lt;/strong&gt; and is &lt;strong&gt;not intended to make available the entire requirement&lt;/strong&gt; of any of the commodities distributed under it to a household or a section of society.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;PDS &lt;/strong&gt;is operated under the &lt;strong&gt;joint responsibility&lt;/strong&gt; of the &lt;strong&gt;Central &lt;/strong&gt;and the &lt;strong&gt;State Governments.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Hence&lt;/span&gt;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Statement 2&amp;nbsp;is correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It &lt;strong&gt;maintains the buffer stock of food grains&lt;/strong&gt; in the &lt;strong&gt;warehouse&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Statement 3&amp;nbsp;is correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Central Government&lt;/strong&gt;, through the &lt;strong&gt;Food Corporation of India&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;strong&gt;FCI&lt;/strong&gt;), has assumed the &lt;strong&gt;responsibility &lt;/strong&gt;for the&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;procurement&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;storage&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;transportation&lt;/strong&gt;, and&lt;strong&gt; bulk allocation of food grains&lt;/strong&gt; to the State Governments.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;operational responsibility&lt;/strong&gt; including allocation within the&lt;strong&gt; State, identification of eligible families, Issue of Ration Cards&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;supervision&lt;/strong&gt; of the functioning of &lt;strong&gt;Fair Price Shops&lt;/strong&gt; (FPSs), etc., rests with the &lt;strong&gt;State Governments.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Under the &lt;strong&gt;PDS&lt;/strong&gt;, presently the &lt;strong&gt;commodities &lt;/strong&gt;namely &lt;strong&gt;wheat, rice, sugar, and kerosene&lt;/strong&gt; are being allocated to the &lt;strong&gt;States/UTs for distribution.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Some&lt;strong&gt; states/UTs also distribute additional items of mass consumption&lt;/strong&gt; through &lt;strong&gt;PDS&lt;/strong&gt; outlets such as &lt;strong&gt;pulses, edible oils, iodized salt, spices,&lt;/strong&gt; etc.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - Change in stock&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gross Fixed Capital Formation (GFCF)&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Gross Fixed Capital Formation refers to the value of acquisitions of new or existing fixed assets (like machinery, buildings, infrastructure, etc.) by the business sector, governments, or households, less disposals of fixed assets.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a measure of investment in fixed assets and serves as a key indicator of economic growth and development.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;GFCF, along with &lt;strong&gt;Change in stock&lt;/strong&gt;, constitutes the total investment within an economy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Change in stock&lt;/strong&gt; refers to the net change in inventories held by businesses during a specific period. This includes goods produced but not yet sold or raw materials and intermediate goods not yet utilized.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Thus, the total investment in an economy is the sum of GFCF and the change in stock.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Change in flow&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;Flow&amp;quot; typically refers to variables measured over a period of time, such as income or expenditure, and is not directly related to investment components like GFCF or stock changes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Net fixed capital&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Net fixed capital is the value of fixed assets after accounting for depreciation. GFCF, in contrast, is a gross measure and does not deduct depreciation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Depreciation&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Depreciation represents the wear and tear or reduction in value of fixed assets over time. It is not a part of investment but rather a deduction from gross investment to calculate net investment.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type:disc&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Marginal standing facility (MSF) is the facility under which banks can borrow money from the RBI when the inter-bank facility dries up.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Scheduled banks can avail from 1-2% of their respective Net Demand and Time Liabilities (NDTL) outstanding at the end of the second preceding fortnight.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - decreases both the money multiplier and the money supply.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fractional Reserve Banking System&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In a fractional reserve banking system, banks are required to keep a certain percentage of their deposits as reserves with the central bank. This percentage is called the reserve requirement.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The remaining portion of deposits can be loaned out, which contributes to the creation of new money in the economy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The money multiplier is the reciprocal of the reserve requirement ratio (Money Multiplier = 1 / Reserve Requirement Ratio).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Impact of Increasing Reserve Requirements&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;An increase in reserve requirements forces banks to hold a larger portion of their deposits as reserves, reducing the amount available for loans.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This reduction in loanable funds directly decreases the potential for money creation in the economy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;As the reserve requirement ratio increases, the money multiplier decreases because banks are restricted from lending as much as before.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;When the money multiplier decreases, the overall money supply in the economy also contracts, as fewer loans result in less money circulating in the system.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Other Options Explained&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1:&lt;/strong&gt; An increase in reserve requirements does not increase the money multiplier or the money supply. Instead, it restricts the ability of banks to lend, leading to a decrease in both.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3:&lt;/strong&gt; While the money supply decreases with an increase in reserve requirements, the money multiplier does not increase. It decreases because the reserve requirement ratio is inversely proportional to the money multiplier.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4:&lt;/strong&gt; An increase in reserve requirements does not increase the money supply. It decreases both the money multiplier and the money supply, as explained above.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Key Concepts Related to Money Multiplier and Money Supply&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Money Multiplier:&lt;/strong&gt; Determines how much money can be created in the economy from a given amount of reserves. Higher reserve requirements lead to a lower multiplier.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Money Supply:&lt;/strong&gt; Includes the total amount of money circulating in the economy, including cash and deposits. When banks lend less, the money supply shrinks.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Reserve Requirement:&lt;/strong&gt; A policy tool used by central banks to regulate money supply and ensure financial stability.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct option is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;from all these, issuing a new currency,&amp;nbsp;borrowing from other countries,&amp;nbsp;borrowing from the market&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Deficit financing&lt;/strong&gt; means filling the gap between government revenue and government expenditure in a government budget either by borrowing funds from the m central bank, the public or printing currency.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Advantages of budget deficit are:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Allows the government to carry out large infrastructure and development projects&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Allows the country to invest in its military at the time of war or unrest&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Deficit spending when done correctly might be a major stimulus to economic growth.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence t&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;he correct option is&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;from all these, issuing a new currency,&amp;nbsp;borrowing from other countries, or borrowing from the market.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - Relative prices&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Relative prices&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Market economics depend on the mechanism of &lt;strong&gt;relative prices&lt;/strong&gt; to allocate scarce resources efficiently.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Relative prices&lt;/strong&gt; refer to the price of one good or service compared to another, acting as a signal for supply and demand.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Producers use price signals to decide what to produce, how much to produce, and for whom to produce.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For example, if the price of a commodity rises due to higher demand, suppliers may allocate more resources to produce that commodity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This mechanism ensures that resources are allocated to their most valued uses in the economy, balancing supply and demand automatically.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Government&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In planned or command economies, governments make decisions about resource allocation. However, in market economies, the government plays a limited role, mostly in regulation and addressing market failures.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Consumers&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;While consumers influence demand, they do not directly allocate resources. Their preferences are reflected through price signals, which guide producers in resource allocation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Real interest rates&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Real interest rates affect savings and investment decisions but are not the primary mechanism for resource allocation in market economies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Match List-I and List-II and select the correct answer from the code given-&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;width: 320px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;List-I&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;List-II&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&amp;nbsp;A. White Revolution&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&amp;nbsp;1. Fertilizer Production&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&amp;nbsp;B. Grey Revolution&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&amp;nbsp;2. Fish Production&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&amp;nbsp;C. Blue Revolution&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&amp;nbsp;3. Cereal Production&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&amp;nbsp;D. Green Revolution&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&amp;nbsp;4. Milk Production&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Code - A B C D

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4 1 2 3&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;White Revolution&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;White Revolution in India also known as Operation Flood.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Operation Flood started in the year 1970 and was aimed to create a nationwide milk grid.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;It was a rural development program initiated by NDDB &amp;ndash; National Dairy Development Board of India.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;White revolution period intended to make India a self-dependent nation in milk production.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Today, India is the world&amp;#39;s largest producer of milk.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Dr. Verghese Kurien is known as the father of the White Revolution in India.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Grey Revolution&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Grey Revolution is associated with increased fertilizer production, which basically means it is related to the main effects of India&amp;#39;s green revolution.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;But only zeroing down to fertilizer won&amp;#39;t be an appropriate thing.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Because the grey revolution includes everything that would take place due to the excessive green revolution.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is actually a glimpse of what can happen if the new agricultural equipment turns things wrong.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Blue Revolution&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Blue Revolution in India was launched during the 7th Five Year Plan(1985-1990) during the sponsorship of the Fish Farmers Development Agency(FFDA) by the Central Government of India.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The main objective is to develop, manage, and promote fisheries to double the farmers&amp;rsquo; income.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(70, 78, 86); &quot;&gt;Dr. Arun Krishnsan and Dr. Hiralal Chaudhari, are&amp;nbsp;known as the fathers of the Blue Revolution.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(70, 78, 86); &quot;&gt;Green Revolution&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(70, 78, 86); &quot;&gt;Green Revolution is associated with agricultural production.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(70, 78, 86); &quot;&gt;It is the period when agriculture of the country was converted into an industrial system due to the adoption of modern methods and techniques like the use of high-yielding variety seeds, tractors, irrigation facilities, pesticides, and fertilizers.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(70, 78, 86); &quot;&gt;The term green revolution was first used by William Gaud and Norman Borlaug is the Father of the Green Revolution.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(70, 78, 86); &quot;&gt;In the year 1965, the government of India launched the Green Revolution with help of M.S. Swaminathan, now known as the father of the Green revolution( India).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - The Price Level&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Price Level&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The price level refers to the average level of prices in the economy, often measured by a price index like the Consumer Price Index (CPI) or the GDP deflator.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;While the price level influences short-run economic fluctuations, it is not a determinant of the long-run level of real GDP.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In the long run, real GDP is determined by factors like resource availability and productivity, not nominal variables such as price level.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;According to classical economic theory, real variables (like real GDP) are determined independently of nominal variables (like price levels) in the long run &amp;mdash; this is known as the classical dichotomy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Thus, price level changes (inflation or deflation) may affect nominal GDP but do not impact the fundamental capacity of an economy to produce goods and services in the long run.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Supply of Labour&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The supply of labour is a critical determinant of the long-run level of real GDP.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Labour supply impacts the economy&amp;#39;s ability to produce goods and services since it determines the workforce available for production.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Factors like population size, labour force participation rate, and demographic trends influence the supply of labour.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Available Natural Resources&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Natural resources, such as minerals, land, and energy sources, play a significant role in determining the long-run productive capacity of an economy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Economies with abundant natural resources often have a higher potential output, provided these resources are utilized efficiently.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;However, long-run GDP also depends on how effectively these resources are managed and whether technological advancements can compensate for resource scarcity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Available Technology&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Technological progress is a key driver of long-run economic growth and higher real GDP.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Advancements in technology improve productivity by enabling more efficient production methods and better utilization of resources.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Innovations and research contribute to sustained economic growth, even in the face of limited resource availability.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Match the following pairs and select the correct answer:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;width: 300px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;1.&amp;nbsp;Goods and Service Tax&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;A. Direct Tax&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;2.&amp;nbsp;Income Tax&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;B. Indirect Tax&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;3.&amp;nbsp;Tax Revenue&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;C. Revenue Receipts&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;4.&amp;nbsp;Capital Receipts&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;D. Capital Budget&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1-B, 2-A, 3-C, 4-D&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;; width: 300px;&quot;&gt;
		&lt;tbody&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td&gt;1.&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;Goods and Service Tax&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td&gt;
				&lt;ul&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Goods and Service Tax is a single, indirect tax levied by the Indian Government.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;It may be one of the country&amp;#39;s most significant tax reforms.&lt;/li&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The bill is designed to bring together from all indirect taxes&lt;/strong&gt; including VAT, Central Excise Tax, Luxury Tax, Service Tax Act, Entertainment Tax and Entry Tax.&lt;/li&gt;
				&lt;/ul&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2.&amp;nbsp;Income Tax&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td&gt;
				&lt;ul&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Income tax is a direct tax which is levied on the incomes of individuals and registered bodies. It is a very big source of government revenues. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;This tax is collected by the income tax department&lt;/li&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;of the government mostly from such points or places where the income is generated. For example, the income tax on the salary income of individuals is deducted from their salaries by their&lt;/li&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;employers who, in turn, deposit it with the government.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
				&lt;/ul&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3.&amp;nbsp;Tax Revenue&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td&gt;
				&lt;ul&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The receipts that do not create any liabilities and do not lead to a claim on the government are called revenue receipts.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;These revenue receipts are non-redeemable and can be classified into two categories, namely: tax revenue and non-tax revenue.&lt;/li&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tax revenues are the vital components of revenue receipts that have been bifurcated for the long term into direct taxes, enterprises, and indirect taxes such as customs duties, excise taxes, and service tax.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
				&lt;/ul&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4.&amp;nbsp;Capital&amp;nbsp;Receipts&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td&gt;
				&lt;ul&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It comes under the capital budget.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
					&lt;li&gt;The government also gets money in terms of loans or from the sale of its assets. Loans must be given back to the agencies from which they have borrowed. Hence, they establish liability.&lt;/li&gt;
				&lt;/ul&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/tbody&gt;
	&lt;/table&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - The slope of the aggregate demand curve&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Wealth Effect:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;When the price level decreases, the real value of money held by consumers increases, making them feel wealthier.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This increased purchasing power encourages higher consumer spending, contributing to a downward slope in the aggregate demand curve.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Interest Rate Effect:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;As the price level decreases, people need less money for transactions and are more likely to save or invest their excess funds.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Increased savings reduce interest rates, which in turn lowers borrowing costs and stimulates investment and consumption, contributing to the downward slope of the aggregate demand curve.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Exchange Rate Effect:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A lower price level in a country makes its goods and services cheaper compared to those of other countries.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This increases exports and reduces imports, boosting net exports and aggregate demand, reinforcing the downward slope of the aggregate demand curve.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The slope of short-run aggregate supply (SRAS):&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The SRAS curve typically slopes upward because, in the short run, some input prices (e.g., wages) are sticky, while output prices can adjust more quickly.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This is unrelated to the wealth, interest rate, or exchange rate effects, which pertain to demand-side factors.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The slope of long-run aggregate supply (LRAS):&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The LRAS curve is vertical, reflecting that in the long run, output is determined by factors like technology, labor, and capital, rather than the price level.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This is not influenced by the wealth, interest rate, or exchange rate effects.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Shifts in the aggregate demand curve:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Factors like changes in government policies, consumer confidence, or global economic conditions cause shifts in the aggregate demand curve.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The wealth, interest rate, and exchange rate effects explain the slope of the curve, not why it shifts.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;It will not affect the co-efficient of Skewness value&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;Skewness:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Skewness is a measure of a distribution&amp;#39;s symmetry.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The mode of a distribution is its highest point.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The mode denotes the x-axis response value that happens with the greatest likelihood.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the tail on one side of the mode is fatter or longer than the tail on the other, the distribution is skewed: it is asymmetrical.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A negative skew in an asymmetrical distribution means the tail on the left side is longer than the tail on the right (left-skewed).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A positive skew means the tail on the right side is longer than the tail on the left (right-skewed) (right-skewed).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Karl Pearson&amp;#39;s co-efficient&amp;nbsp;of Skewness:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Pearson coefficient of skewness is a method devised by Karl Pearson for determining skewness in a sample using descriptive statistics such as the mean and mode.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Skewness is a metric for determining the shape of a set of data.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Pearson&amp;rsquo;s coefficient of skewness (second method) is calculated by multiplying the difference between the mean and median, multiplied by three. The result is divided by the standard deviation.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Formula: Karl Pearson&amp;#39;s coefficient =&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:16px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\({\bar X - Z}\over \sigma\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:16px;&quot;&gt;where,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\bar X = Mean \)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(Z = Mode\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\sigma = \text{Standard Deviation}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;​If each value in a given set of data is divided by 4,&amp;nbsp;It will not affect the co-efficient of Skewness value.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - The price level and real output&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The price level and real output&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In macroeconomics, aggregate supply and demand represent the total supply of goods and services produced within an economy and the total demand for those goods and services at a particular price level.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;price level&lt;/strong&gt; is a measure of the average prices of goods and services in an economy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;When aggregate demand exceeds aggregate supply, the price level tends to rise, leading to inflation. Conversely, when aggregate supply exceeds aggregate demand, prices generally fall, leading to deflation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Real output&lt;/strong&gt; refers to the total quantity of goods and services produced in an economy, adjusted for changes in the price level (i.e., real GDP).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;To bring aggregate supply and demand into balance, adjustments occur through changes in the price level and real output. For instance:
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;If aggregate demand increases, prices may rise, and firms may expand production to meet the increased demand.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;If aggregate demand decreases, prices may fall, and firms may reduce output to avoid excess inventory.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This mechanism ensures equilibrium between aggregate supply and demand in the short run and long run.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The real rate of interest and money supply&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The real rate of interest is the nominal interest rate adjusted for inflation. It influences investment and consumption decisions but does not directly balance aggregate supply and demand.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The money supply impacts liquidity and interest rates in an economy, but it is a monetary policy tool rather than an adjustment mechanism for supply and demand equilibrium.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Government expenditure and taxes&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Government expenditure and taxes are fiscal policy tools used to influence aggregate demand. While they can shift demand, they are not the primary mechanisms for balancing aggregate supply and demand.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The saving rate and net exports&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The saving rate affects the availability of funds for investment, while net exports contribute to overall demand in an economy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;However, these factors are components of aggregate demand and not direct mechanisms to balance supply and demand.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

