&lt;br /&gt;
Select the correct answer using the code given below:

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Industrial Policy Resolution 1956 (IPR 1956) classified industries into three categories.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The first category comprised industries which would be exclusively owned by the state;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The second category consisted of industries in which the private sector could supplement the efforts of the state sector, with the state taking the sole responsibility for starting new units;&lt;/p&gt;
The third category consisted of the remaining industries which were to be in the private sector.

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - An increase in money supply increases level of income and reduces rate of interest.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Keynesian Model Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In the Keynesian model, the price level is assumed to be fixed in the short run, meaning there is no inflationary impact due to changes in money supply.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;When the money supply increases, individuals and businesses have more liquidity available. This leads to greater spending and investment activity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Higher spending and investment stimulate aggregate demand, which directly increases the level of income or output in the economy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Additionally, the increase in money supply lowers interest rates because banks have excess reserves, making borrowing cheaper for consumers and businesses.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Lower interest rates further encourage borrowing and investment, amplifying the positive impact on income levels.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Relevant Concepts in Keynesian Economics:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Money Supply:&lt;/strong&gt; Refers to the total amount of monetary assets available in an economy at a given time. An increase in money supply leads to more liquidity and lower interest rates.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Interest Rates:&lt;/strong&gt; The cost of borrowing money; lower interest rates encourage borrowing and investment, boosting economic activity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Aggregate Demand:&lt;/strong&gt; Represents the total demand for goods and services in an economy. Higher liquidity and lower interest rates lead to increased aggregate demand.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Income Levels:&lt;/strong&gt; In the Keynesian framework, income levels rise when aggregate demand increases, as businesses respond by producing more goods and services.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Short-Run Analysis:&lt;/strong&gt; The assumption of fixed prices applies to short-run scenarios where output adjustments occur without significant inflationary pressures.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Brief Overview of Other Options:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option suggesting a fall in money supply:&lt;/strong&gt; A decrease in money supply would lead to less liquidity, higher interest rates, reduced borrowing, and a decline in income levels. This is contrary to the Keynesian model&amp;#39;s prediction.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option suggesting reduced income with increased money supply:&lt;/strong&gt; An increase in money supply does not reduce income; it stimulates aggregate demand and raises income levels.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option suggesting increased interest rates with increased money supply:&lt;/strong&gt; Increased money supply lowers interest rates due to excess liquidity, not the opposite.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

